  <data key="d3">no longer talked in the same incoherent manner of my own crimes;
sufficient for me was the consciousness of them. By the utmost self-violence I
curbed the imperious voice of wretchedness, which sometimes desired to declare
itself to the whole world, and my manners were calmer and more composed than
they had ever been since my journey to the sea of ice. A few days before we left Paris on our way to Switzerland, I received the
following letter from Elizabeth: “My dear Friend, “It gave me the great</data>
